restore the ILC population. So the exact mechanism, we haven't know

253
00:15:17.332 --> 00:15:18.951
yet. Yeah.

254
00:15:20.612 --> 00:15:23.932
I have a question. So is there a direct effect of the high lipid

255
00:15:24.012 --> 00:15:27.492
concentration on the ILCs in terms of recruitment or differentiation?

256
00:15:28.012 --> 00:15:29.812
And why would that just happen in the liver-

257
00:15:30.032 --> 00:15:30.132
Yeah

258
00:15:30.332 --> 00:15:30.992
... not the other organs?

259
00:15:31.002 --> 00:15:34.872
So yeah. That's a great question. So because of time, I haven't shown

260
00:15:34.952 --> 00:15:38.592
here. Actually, the decrease of ILC in the liver is

261
00:15:38.712 --> 00:15:39.332
because,

262
00:15:40.272 --> 00:15:41.732
in the macrophage, in the

263
00:15:42.932 --> 00:15:46.512
lipid-enriched condition, they will decrease the expression of

264
00:15:46.632 --> 00:15:50.412
IL-15, which made the decreased number of ILC.

265
00:15:51.092 --> 00:15:52.592
Yeah, it's not ILC itself.

266
00:15:52.952 --> 00:15:56.672
So did you see that effect on ILC2s and 3s as well, or just ILC1?

267
00:15:56.712 --> 00:15:57.122
Or did you not-

268
00:15:57.512 --> 00:16:01.392
So we haven't specifically looked at ILC2 and the 3 in

269
00:16:01.452 --> 00:16:04.032
the liver because there is very few cells in the liver.

270
00:16:04.072 --> 00:16:06.132
So most abundant one is the ILC1.

271
00:16:08.712 --> 00:16:09.152
Anyone else?

272
00:16:10.412 --> 00:16:11.372
Okay. Thank you, Peng.

273
00:16:11.432 --> 00:16:12.212
Okay. Thank you.

274
00:16:16.932 --> 00:16:20.432
All right. So next one up, we have Sepideh Gholamin.

275
00:16:21.772 --> 00:16:25.392
So please come up to the stage, and she'll tell us about neutrophil extracellular

276
00:16:25.412 --> 00:16:28.332
traps and its role in colorectal cancer metastasis.

277
00:16:32.632 --> 00:16:34.742
There you go.

278
00:16:34.802 --> 00:16:38.452
Great. Thank you so much for the programs committee to allow us to

279
00:16:38.532 --> 00:16:41.852
present our work entitled "Neutrophil Extracellular Trap Inhibition

280
00:16:42.332 --> 00:16:46.072
Mitigates the Tumor Necrosis and Metastasis in Colorectal Cancer."

281
00:16:46.552 --> 00:16:48.252
I have no relevant disclosures for here.

282
00:16:48.692 --> 00:16:52.532
So just to set the stage, I'm a surgical oncologist, and I really focus on

283
00:16:52.552 --> 00:16:56.392
liver metastasis, and I have had a really focus clinically.

284
00:16:56.432 --> 00:17:00.061
And I think some of the statistics that I present here are not really

285
00:17:00.092 --> 00:17:03.812
exciting to show that really the early rise in the early onset

286
00:17:03.852 --> 00:17:07.682
colorectal cancer has been increasing, with increasing incidents in those

287
00:17:07.732 --> 00:17:11.633
under 50. We now also know that it now presents a number

288
00:17:11.752 --> 00:17:15.633
one leading cause of cancer death-related mortality in patients under 50, both

289
00:17:15.692 --> 00:17:19.192
in women and men. And as a surgeon, I see

290
00:17:19.272 --> 00:17:23.212
essentially these patients, despite really the curative intent resections

291
00:17:23.232 --> 00:17:27.212
that we offer, that most patients will recur with metastatic disease, and this

292
00:17:27.272 --> 00:17:31.192
is over 70% of the time. And this is

293
00:17:31.232 --> 00:17:35.172
really the driver of mortality. And so given these findings,

294
00:17:35.232 --> 00:17:39.122
and specifically the tumor microenvironment of the liver itself, I

295
00:17:39.132 --> 00:17:42.732
think we're facing some barriers, and specifically with drug

296
00:17:42.742 --> 00:17:46.712
development. We've seen limited infiltrating T cells

297
00:17:46.752 --> 00:17:49.592
in there. We see increased myeloid suppression cells.

298
00:17:49.632 --> 00:17:53.112
And all of these are barriers to immunotherapy drug development in liver

299
00:17:53.132 --> 00:17:56.492
metastasis. So with that, our lab focus here is really

300
00:17:56.712 --> 00:17:59.992
development of immune-augmenting therapies for colorectal liver

301
00:18:00.052 --> 00:18:03.752
metastasis, and specifically defining the mechanism that drive

302
00:18:03.772 --> 00:18:06.952
therapeutic resistance and metastasis.

303
00:18:07.032 --> 00:18:10.792
So to set the stage, we basically started a project that was really

304
00:18:10.802 --> 00:18:14.382
interest in looking in specifically in NETs and

305
00:18:14.532 --> 00:18:18.432
neutrophil extracellular traps, which are essentially extracellular

306
00:18:18.472 --> 00:18:22.352
DNA that is secreted by neutrophils, and

307
00:18:22.392 --> 00:18:25.532
with some granular protein degradation product.

308
00:18:25.962 --> 00:18:27.932
And this is in the content of necrosis.

309
00:18:28.372 --> 00:18:32.212
And all of this work was reallysparked off when I joined

310
00:18:32.472 --> 00:18:35.972
Cold Spring Harbor Lab about now four years ago by a really

311
00:18:36.132 --> 00:18:40.112
incredible scientist, both Michela Eaglebud as well as Jose Drover, really

312
00:18:40.152 --> 00:18:42.752
describing NETs in the context of necrosis.

313
00:18:43.042 --> 00:18:46.392
Since we know that necrosis has been associated with worsening

314
00:18:46.752 --> 00:18:50.732
outcomes, specifically driving survival, they asked the question whether NETs

315
00:18:50.742 --> 00:18:54.032
are actually driving necrosis in these breast cancer tumors and lung

316
00:18:54.052 --> 00:18:57.462
metastases in their model. So what Jose in this work has been

317
00:18:57.532 --> 00:19:01.392
really nicely presented in "Nature Medicine," I won't go

318
00:19:01.452 --> 00:19:05.262
into that, but this really led us to the question when we saw that in

319
00:19:05.292 --> 00:19:09.172
these PAD4 mice knockouts, which lacks the ability to

320
00:19:09.212 --> 00:19:13.192
form NETs and extracellular traps, we saw that the amount

321
00:19:13.252 --> 00:19:17.112
of necrosis decreased in the genetic

322
00:19:17.272 --> 00:19:19.332
deficient mice versus the wild types.

323
00:19:19.342 --> 00:19:23.152
And not only saw we a decrease in the necrosis, but also as well in lung

324
00:19:23.172 --> 00:19:26.902
metastases. So we then looked into this in a

325
00:19:26.932 --> 00:19:30.822
colorectal cancer model specifically because we knew as clinicians that

326
00:19:31.052 --> 00:19:34.722
necrosis is a bad driver of metastasis as well as

327
00:19:35.712 --> 00:19:39.262
survival. And what we conventionally always thought is that necrosis is

328
00:19:39.492 --> 00:19:43.432
different really by this tumor size, really outgrowing its blood supply and

329
00:19:43.552 --> 00:19:45.772
possibly hypoxia conventionally.

330
00:19:45.832 --> 00:19:49.672
But we didn't really see any correlation between size and the degree

331
00:19:49.712 --> 00:19:53.532
of necrosis when we looked at the necrosis score that I've shown here

332
00:19:53.612 --> 00:19:57.472
under low, intermediate, and high grade of these H&amp;E stains

333
00:19:57.512 --> 00:20:00.732
from these patients that were prospectively collected.

334
00:20:01.212 --> 00:20:04.892
We then looked into the number of NETs and the area of netosis

335
00:20:04.972 --> 00:20:08.872
in these tumors on these patient slides and saw that with

336
00:20:08.932 --> 00:20:12.752
increasing necrosis score, the number of NETs increased, as well

337
00:20:12.832 --> 00:20:16.312
as the presenting stage of the patients with the time of disease.

338
00:20:16.392 --> 00:20:20.252
So essentially, patients with stage four disease and higher stage of disease

339
00:20:20.552 --> 00:20:23.572
had higher amounts of necrosis on their tumor slides.

340
00:20:24.032 --> 00:20:27.552
When we then looked spatially, we noticed that the tumors

341
00:20:27.652 --> 00:20:31.372
that were filled with necrosis had higher enrichment of

342
00:20:31.492 --> 00:20:35.172
NETs compared to those tumors that did not have

343
00:20:35.532 --> 00:20:37.632
necrotic or had non-necrotic areas.

344
00:20:38.052 --> 00:20:41.841
And so this really led us further to look into the peripheral blood

345
00:20:41.872 --> 00:20:45.612
system. And then we saw that essentially there's increased

346
00:20:45.652 --> 00:20:49.112
neutrophils, and specifically neutrophils that are primed to

347
00:20:50.032 --> 00:20:53.952
form NETs with the markers of citrulline, histone Cit3.

348
00:20:53.972 --> 00:20:57.292
And we saw that the patients with colorectal cancer, compared to the healthy

349
00:20:57.312 --> 00:21:00.722
controls, had elevated NET levels compared to those

350
00:21:01.272 --> 00:21:05.072
healthy controls. We then went into the public databases and

351
00:21:05.092 --> 00:21:08.932
really looked into it, and you can really see that this is further validated in

352
00:21:09.012 --> 00:21:12.952
other studies that patients with colorectal cancer and breast cancer, these are two

353
00:21:13.112 --> 00:21:17.032
examples from public database, have increased PMNs in their blood

354
00:21:17.072 --> 00:21:20.982
circulation. When we looked further, and I won't go into the story of it

355
00:21:21.052 --> 00:21:23.012
too much, there was a specific subgroup of

356
00:21:23.912 --> 00:21:27.332
circulating neutrophils, specifically those that are like one

357
00:21:27.392 --> 00:21:31.352
CD177 low, and this was consistent again with the breast data that was even

358
00:21:31.401 --> 00:21:35.252
more striking, in which these patients have a higher level of these

359
00:21:35.412 --> 00:21:38.952
177 neutrophils. And those are specifically

360
00:21:39.032 --> 00:21:42.972
trapped in these tumor vessels that you can see with the cyanine,

361
00:21:43.052 --> 00:21:46.352
which is the NETs released with essentially DAPI,

362
00:21:47.092 --> 00:21:50.812
citrullinated histone 3, as well as MPO as a marker for these NETs

363
00:21:51.092 --> 00:21:53.952
being trapped in this. So this really then further

364
00:21:53.961 --> 00:21:57.872
led to our hypothesis that perhaps

365
00:21:57.912 --> 00:22:01.862
what we are seeing is that these NETs get trapped in these tumors, forming

366
00:22:01.912 --> 00:22:05.032
in the vessels and get trapped there without being able to

367
00:22:05.072 --> 00:22:08.912
extravasate, leading to hypoxia and necrosis itself versus

368
00:22:08.952 --> 00:22:12.792
it being a passive phenomenon. So our question really and hypothesis

369
00:22:12.832 --> 00:22:16.572
were: Are NETs active drivers of tumor necrosis and

370
00:22:16.612 --> 00:22:18.712
metastases in colorectal cancer?

371
00:22:20.092 --> 00:22:23.972
To get to the experimental design and how we wanted to answer the causality here,

372
00:22:24.052 --> 00:22:27.432
we looked at two different models, one of which was the

373
00:22:27.452 --> 00:22:31.272
pharmacological model and then a genetic inhibition model

374
00:22:31.282 --> 00:22:34.812
here. Just to briefly describe the model, this is a really brilliant

375
00:22:34.992 --> 00:22:38.792
model that I think as a clinician, I highly find this very helpful

376
00:22:38.812 --> 00:22:42.212
because it really faithfully recapitulates what we see in the patients.

377
00:22:42.812 --> 00:22:46.232
This model has been invented by Dr.

378
00:22:46.772 --> 00:22:50.472
Peter Wescott, who's my lab partner at Cold Spring Harbor Lab, and it's

379
00:22:50.532 --> 00:22:53.882
essentially a mouse organoid model that has been genetically engineered with the

380
00:22:53.932 --> 00:22:57.582
four most common driver mutation, and really phenotypically and

381
00:22:57.832 --> 00:23:01.312
histopathologically shows and is similar to the

382
00:23:01.372 --> 00:23:04.312
MSS and microsatellite proficient tumors.

383
00:23:04.702 --> 00:23:08.662
And so with a colonoscopic injection, these tumors get injected into

384
00:23:08.712 --> 00:23:12.492
the rectum and the colon, and essentially then over

385
00:23:12.812 --> 00:23:16.192
the period of six weeks, we see metastases spontaneously.

386
00:23:16.692 --> 00:23:20.092
These mice were either treated with disulfiram for the pharmacologic group, or we

387
00:23:20.252 --> 00:23:22.952
used a PAD4 knockout mouse similar to Jose's work,

388
00:23:23.792 --> 00:23:26.592
that again, unable to form NETs.

389
00:23:27.572 --> 00:23:31.492
As our outcomes measures, we looked at NETs, we looked at necrosis, and the

390
00:23:31.532 --> 00:23:34.112
number of liver metastases to look into this.

391
00:23:34.652 --> 00:23:38.222
So first, looking at the PAD4 genetic model end

392
00:23:38.272 --> 00:23:42.232
results, we show again that similar again to the breast results that

393
00:23:42.312 --> 00:23:46.292
the PAD4 knockout mice show decreased number

394
00:23:46.372 --> 00:23:49.412
of necrosis as well as decreased number of

395
00:23:49.452 --> 00:23:53.352
metastases. This is measured by the number of liver metastases as well

396
00:23:53.492 --> 00:23:57.292
as the area of liver metastases. We then further looked

397
00:23:57.352 --> 00:23:58.632
into the pharmacologic

398
00:23:59.532 --> 00:24:01.792
inhibition assays and using disulfiram.

399
00:24:01.892 --> 00:24:04.432
So disulfiram actually inhibits grastromin D.

400
00:24:04.602 --> 00:24:08.012
It's like the release of NETs is inhibited by this drug molecule.

401
00:24:08.022 --> 00:24:11.532
And the reason we really picked this is because this is an FDA-approved drug, and

402
00:24:11.552 --> 00:24:15.472
we really had a translational focus wanting to drive this into the clinic, perhaps.

403
00:24:16.112 --> 00:24:20.092
So we chose that drug, and you can see that the mice that are treated with a

404
00:24:20.112 --> 00:24:24.100
disulfiram diet had decreased number of NETs.And then

405
00:24:24.140 --> 00:24:27.940
furthermore, we also looked at histologically, they have decreased necrosis

406
00:24:28.020 --> 00:24:31.880
formation in these tumors. When you look at the primary tumor, the

407
00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:35.810
size of the tumors actually did not, again, change with disulfiram alone,

408
00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:39.520
again, showing that necrosis was not necessarily linked

409
00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:43.560
to just tumor necrosis itself by size and kind of

410
00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:46.300
that conventional way of hypothesizing.

411
00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:46.910
But

412
00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:51.130
most importantly to us was that, the treated mice with

413
00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:55.030
disulfiram did have decreased number of liver metastases by,

414
00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:58.480
again, area of measurement as well as the number of liver

415
00:24:58.500 --> 00:24:59.260
metastases.

416
00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:04.300
So we now have really had this observation that these NETs are

417
00:25:04.700 --> 00:25:08.480
sort of enriched and informed in these tumors that are in these

418
00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:12.460
necrotic region. So then really the next question was, how do

419
00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:16.090
these necrotic tumors drive metastases in colorectal cancer

420
00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:20.070
particular in this model? So to answer this question, we looked at

421
00:25:20.300 --> 00:25:23.380
single cell sequencing of tissue samples of patients that

422
00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:27.360
underwent liver resections. We looked at necrotic versus

423
00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:31.440
non-necrotic tumors. And when we look at this tSNE plot, you could see that

424
00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:34.520
there was a cluster of enrichment of cells in the

425
00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:38.390
necrotic tumors compared to the non-necrotic tumors,

426
00:25:38.820 --> 00:25:42.160
which showed really increased signal pathways of

427
00:25:42.220 --> 00:25:46.080
EMT, hypoxia, and inflammation. So for EMT, you can see

428
00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:49.900
here the signal genes like vimentin as well as SNAI1.

429
00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:53.800
For hypoxia, we saw like VEGF-A an increase.

430
00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:53.920
And

431
00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:58.320
then we saw a lot of the inflammatory signaling that really

432
00:25:58.500 --> 00:26:02.380
further kind of deepened and supported our hypothesis that there is

433
00:26:02.540 --> 00:26:05.700
potentially EMT regulation increase as well as

434
00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:09.720
hypoxic changes in these areas. So we then went back to our

435
00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:14.440
human sample tissues and wanted to validate this EMT signaling

436
00:26:14.460 --> 00:26:18.220
that we had observed in our single cell data from those patient samples, and

437
00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:22.820
did RNA scope. So at the RNA level, you see that SNAI1

438
00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:26.180
is increased in the perinecrotic region compared to the

439
00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:29.760
non-necrotic regions. E-cadherin was, as expected,

440
00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:33.590
lower in the perinecrotic regions compared to the non-necrotic

441
00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:37.449
regions. We then further even went at the protein level and confirmed

442
00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:40.860
this and saw that in both the primary tumor as well as the liver

443
00:26:40.880 --> 00:26:44.160
metastases, the perinecrotic regions had increased

444
00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:47.920
signaling of SNAI versus the non-necrotic

445
00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:50.880
region. This was, again, similarly seen in the liver

446
00:26:50.920 --> 00:26:54.760
metastases. And then finally, we went then into our mouse model and wanted to

447
00:26:54.820 --> 00:26:58.680
validate that similar finding. So we looked at those tumors that were harvested

448
00:26:58.720 --> 00:26:59.040
from those

449
00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:03.700
mice that had tumor-bearings mice, and we saw that the

450
00:27:03.740 --> 00:27:07.580
perinecrotic regions in those tumors had increased level of

451
00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:10.960
vimentin versus those in the non-necrotic.

452
00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.990
Looking even further, and I think in the interest of time, I won't belabor this,

453
00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:18.920
but we did look into the hematopoietic sort of compartment and

454
00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:21.190
looked systemically what is happening.

455
00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:24.980
And you could see that in our mouse model, the tumor-bearing mice had

456
00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:28.949
increased levels of GMPs as well as neutrophils, and

457
00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:32.770
really no significant changes in monocytes and T cells were observed.

458
00:27:33.740 --> 00:27:37.720
So again, as a surgical scientist, I really have always a therapeutic implication

459
00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:39.370
and that's what I really care about.

460
00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:41.340
Ultimately, how can I get this to our patients?

461
00:27:41.420 --> 00:27:45.180
So when we observe that these NETs are trapped in the vessels leading to

462
00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:49.180
potential hypoxia and the changes that we saw in the single cell, the next

463
00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:52.860
really common obvious question for me was, would this NET

464
00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:56.180
inhibition, can be combined with other conventional ways of

465
00:27:57.640 --> 00:28:01.160
therapeutically how we're treating colorectal cancer, and can this

466
00:28:01.240 --> 00:28:05.220
improve perhaps the responses? Maybe specifically

467
00:28:05.260 --> 00:28:08.860
for chemotherapy, can we increase the delivery of the

468
00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:12.620
chemotherapeutic agents to these liver metastases and the primary tumor

469
00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:16.500
when we are giving NET inhibition in addition to chemotherapy?

470
00:28:17.060 --> 00:28:21.040
So what we did for these set of experiments is, again, we used the same

471
00:28:21.100 --> 00:28:24.900
AKPS model. In the primary tumor, we saw

472
00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:29.170
that the primary tumor size had increased responses

473
00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:32.380
with the disulfiram plus the chemotherapy gone.

474
00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:36.560
For chemotherapy, we used a standard FOLFOX, which is standardly used

475
00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:39.340
in those patients with colorectal cancer.

476
00:28:39.350 --> 00:28:43.060
And I think more importantly and strikingly, is that the lumbar liver

477
00:28:43.100 --> 00:28:46.400
metastases were significantly decreased in the

478
00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:50.100
combination group compared to those who all had system

479
00:28:50.520 --> 00:28:51.620
chemotherapy alone.

480
00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.350
So in conclusion, I hope I was able to show you that

481
00:28:57.280 --> 00:29:01.040
really we have this conceptual model in which we think that colorectal

482
00:29:01.100 --> 00:29:04.820
cancer tumors drive really increased myeloid

483
00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:08.340
skew systemically. And so we see increased

484
00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:10.520
circulation of neutrophils in these.

485
00:29:10.580 --> 00:29:14.560
These then are able to form NETs and specifically, they

486
00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:18.320
get trapped in the vessels of these necrotic tumor regions leading to

487
00:29:18.360 --> 00:29:22.340
hypoxia and also EMT signal changes and activations of

488
00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:26.080
other inflammatory programs, ultimately leading to increased liver

489
00:29:26.120 --> 00:29:29.500
metastases. And we think that targeting this access would

490
00:29:29.540 --> 00:29:33.520
be an interesting therapeutic strategy for also combinations with

491
00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:36.860
systemic therapy and hopefully in the future, immunotherapy, which is what we're

492
00:29:36.900 --> 00:29:40.160
working on now. So with that, again, I really want to thank

493
00:29:40.920 --> 00:29:44.880
